Ælle of Sussex.label: Ælle of Sussex
Ælle of Sussex.description: Ælle is recorded in early sources as the first king of the South Saxons, reigning in what is now called Sussex, England, from 477 to perhaps as late as 514. Wikipedia

Æthelbald of Mercia.label: Æthelbald of Mercia
Æthelbald of Mercia.description: Æthelbald was the King of Mercia, in what is now the English Midlands from 716 until he was killed in 757. Wikipedia

Æthelberht II of East Anglia.label: Æthelberht II of East Anglia
Æthelberht II of East Anglia.description: Æthelberht, also called Saint Ethelbert the King, was an eighth-century saint and a king of East Anglia, the Anglo-Saxon kingdom which today includes the English counties of Norfolk and Suffolk. Wikipedia

Æthelwold of East Anglia.label: Æthelwold of East Anglia
Æthelwold of East Anglia.description: Æthelwold, also known as Æthelwald or Æþelwald, was a 7th-century king of East Anglia, the long-lived Anglo-Saxon kingdom which today includes the English counties of Norfolk and Suffolk. Wikipedia

Ablai Khan.label: Ablai Khan
Ablai Khan.description: Wali-ullah Abul-Mansur Khan better known as Ablai Khan was a Kazakh khan of the Middle jüz. Born as Wali-ullah Abul-Mansur Khan, Ablai Khan belonged to the senior branch of descendants of the 15th century founder of the Kazakh state, Janybek Khan. Wikipedia

Aktisanes.label: Aktisanes
Aktisanes.description: Aktisanes is a Nubian king who is mentioned by the Greek historian Hecataeus of Abdera. He is perhaps identical with Menmaatre-Setepenamun Gatisen known from Nubian sources. Wikipedia

Aldfrith of Northumbria.label: Aldfrith of Northumbria
Aldfrith of Northumbria.description: Aldfrith was king of Northumbria from 685 until his death. He is described by early writers such as Bede, Alcuin and Stephen of Ripon as a man of great learning. Some of his works and some letters written to him survive. Wikipedia

Al-Muzaffar Umar.label: Al-Muzaffar Umar
Al-Muzaffar Umar.description: Al-Muzaffar Taqi al-Din Umar was the Ayyubid prince of Hama from 1179 to 1191 and a general of Saladin. He was the son of Saladin's brother Nur al-Din Shahanshah and brother of Farrukh Shah of Baalbek. Wikipedia

Apollodotus II.label: Apollodotus II
Apollodotus II.description: Apollodotus II, was an Indo-Greek king who ruled in the western and eastern parts of Punjab. Bopearachchi dates him to circa 80–65 BCE, and R. C. Senior to circa 85–65 BCE. Wikipedia

Archduke Eugen of Austria.label: Archduke Eugen of Austria
Archduke Eugen of Austria.description: Archduke Eugen Ferdinand Pius Bernhard Felix Maria of Austria-Teschen was an Archduke of Austria and a Prince of Hungary and Bohemia. He was the last Grand Master of the Teutonic Knights from the Habsburg dynasty. Wikipedia

Baskakeren.label: Baskakeren
Baskakeren.description:
Baskakeren was a king of Kush. He was likely a son of King Malewiebamani and the younger brother of King Amanineteyerike. He succeeded King Amanineteyerike to the throne.
Baskakeren is so far only known from his small pyramid in Nuri. Wikipedia

Axayacatl.label: Axayacatl
Axayacatl.description:
Axayacatl of the Postclassic Mesoamerican Aztec Empire and city of Tenochtitlan, who reigned from 1469 to 1481.
He is chiefly remembered for subjugating Tlatelolco, Tenochtitlan's sister city, in 1473. Wikipedia

Bindusara.label: Bindusara
Bindusara.description: Bindusara Maurya was emperor of the Maurya Empire from 298 BC – 272 BC. During his reign, the empire expanded southwards. He had two well-known sons, Susima and Ashoka, who were the viceroys of Takshashila and Ujjain. Wikipedia

Borandukht.label: Borandukht
Borandukht.description: Boran or Poran, or more correctly Burandokht or Purandokht, was the daughter of the King Khosrau II. She was one of only two women on the throne of the Sasanian Empire. Wikipedia

Branimir of Croatia.label: Branimir of Croatia
Branimir of Croatia.description: Branimir was a ruler of the Duchy of Croatia who reigned as knez from 879 to 892. His country recevied papal recognition as a state from Pope John VIII on 7 June 879. Wikipedia

Cissa of Sussex.label: Cissa of Sussex
Cissa of Sussex.description: Cissa was part of an Anglo-Saxon invasion force that landed in three ships at a place called Cymensora in 477AD. The invasion was led by Cissa's father Ælle and included his two brothers. They are said to have fought against the local Britons. Wikipedia

Constantine Mavrocordatos.label: Constantine Mavrocordatos
Constantine Mavrocordatos.description: Constantine Mavrocordatos was a Greek noble who served as Prince of Wallachia and Prince of Moldavia at several intervals. Wikipedia

Cynethryth.label: Cynethryth
Cynethryth.description: Cynethryth was a Queen of Mercia and wife of King Offa of Mercia and mother of King Ecgfrith of Mercia. Cynethryth is the only Anglo-Saxon Queen consort in whose name coinage was definitely issued. Wikipedia

Daher el-Omar.label: Daher el-Omar
Daher el-Omar.description: Daher el-Omar was the autonomous Arab ruler of the Galilee region during the mid-18th century. The founder of modern Haifa, he fortified many cities, among them Acre. Wikipedia

Dietrich I von Hengebach.label: Dietrich I von Hengebach
Dietrich I von Hengebach.description: Dietrich I von Hengebach was the Archbishop of Cologne. He was elected in 1208. He supported Otto of the House of Welf as Holy Roman Emperor and was excommunicated in 1212 by Innocent III. Wikipedia

Ecgric of East Anglia.label: Ecgric of East Anglia
Ecgric of East Anglia.description: Ecgric was a king of East Anglia, the independent Anglo-Saxon kingdom that today includes the English counties of Norfolk and Suffolk. Wikipedia

Basarab I of Wallachia.label: Basarab I of Wallachia
Basarab I of Wallachia.description: Basarab I the Founder Ivanco Basarab according to a medieval Serbian document was voivode or prince of Wallachia. Wikipedia

Archebius.label: Archebius
Archebius.description: Archebius Dikaios Nikephoros was an Indo-Greek king who ruled in the area of Taxila. Osmund Bopearachchi dates him to circa 90–80 BCE, and R. C. Senior to about the same period. Wikipedia

Dionysios Soter.label: Dionysios Soter
Dionysios Soter.description: Dionysios Soter was an Indo-Greek king in the area of eastern Punjab. Wikipedia

Emperor Chūkyō.label: Emperor Chūkyō
Emperor Chūkyō.description: Emperor Chūkyō was the 85th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession. His reign spanned only months in 1221, and he was not officially listed amongst the emperors until 1870 ... Wikipedia

Empress Kōgyoku.label: Empress Kōgyoku
Empress Kōgyoku.description:
Empress Kōgyoku, also known as Empress Saimei, was the 35th and 37th monarch of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.
Kōgyoku's reign spanned the years from 642–645. Her reign as Saimei encompassed 655–661. Wikipedia

Emperor Rokujō.label: Emperor Rokujō
Emperor Rokujō.description: Emperor Rokujō was the 79th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession. His reign spanned the years from 1165 through 1168. Wikipedia

Emperor Toba.label: Emperor Toba
Emperor Toba.description:
Emperor Toba was the 74th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.
Toba's reign spanned the years from 1107 through 1123. Wikipedia

Empress Meishō.label: Empress Meishō
Empress Meishō.description:
Empress Meishō was the 109th Imperial ruler of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.
Meishō's reign spanned the years from 1629 to 1643.
In the history of Japan, Meishō was the seventh of eight women to become empress regnant. Wikipedia

Enlil-bani.label: Enlil-bani
Enlil-bani.description: Enlil-bāni, ca. 1798 BC – 1775 BC or 1860-1837 BC, was the 10th king of the 1st Dynasty of Isin and reigned 24 years according to the Ur-Isin kinglist. He is best known for the legendary and perhaps apocryphal manner of his ascendancy. Wikipedia

Ferdinand Kettler.label: Ferdinand Kettler
Ferdinand Kettler.description: Ferdinand Kettler was Duke of Courland and Semigallia from 1730 to 1737. Ferdinand was the son of Jacob Kettler and Louise Charlotte of Brandenburg. Married in 1730 to Johanna Magdalene of Saxe-Weissenfels. Wikipedia

Friedrich Kettler.label: Friedrich Kettler
Friedrich Kettler.description:
Friedrich Kettler was Duke of Courland from 1587 to 1642.
He was the son of Gotthard Kettler, the first Duke of Courland. Wikipedia

Gajah Mada.label: Gajah Mada
Gajah Mada.description: Gajah Mada was, according to Javanese old manuscripts, poems and mythology, a powerful military leader and mahapatih or prime minister of the Majapahit Empire, credited with bringing the empire to its peak of glory. Wikipedia

Gavril Radomir of Bulgaria.label: Gavril Radomir of Bulgaria
Gavril Radomir of Bulgaria.description: Gavril Radomir, normally rendered as Gabriel Radomir in English and Gavriil Romanos in Greek, was the ruler of the First Bulgarian Empire from October 1014 to August or September 1015. He was the son of Samuel of Bulgaria. Wikipedia

Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg.label: Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg
Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg.description: Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg was Archbishop-Elector of Cologne. After pursuing an ecclesiastical career, he won a close election in the Cathedral chapter of Cologne over Ernst of Bavaria. Wikipedia

Gediminas.label: Gediminas
Gediminas.description: Gediminas was Grand Duke of Lithuania from 1315 or 1316 until his death. He is credited with founding this political entity and expanding its territory which, at the time of his death, spanned the area ranging from the Baltic Sea to the Black Sea. Wikipedia

Iter-pisha.label: Iter-pisha
Iter-pisha.description: Iter-piša, inscribed in cuneiform as i-te-er-pi/pi4-ša and meaning "Her command is surpassing", ca. 1769–1767 BC or ca. 1833–1831 BC, was the 12th king of Isin during the Old Babylonian period. Wikipedia

Ithobaal I.label: Ithobaal I
Ithobaal I.description: Ithobaal I was a king of Tyre who founded a new dynasty. During his reign, Tyre expanded its power on the mainland, making all of Phoenicia its territory as far north as Beirut, including Sidon, and even a part of the island of Cyprus. Wikipedia

Jehoash of Judah.label: Jehoash of Judah
Jehoash of Judah.description: Jehoash or Joas, sometimes written Joash or Joás, was the eighth king of Judah since his fourth great-grandfather Rehoboam, and the sole surviving son of Ahaziah. His mother was Zibiah of Beersheba. Wikipedia

Jovan Vladimir.label: Jovan Vladimir
Jovan Vladimir.description: Jovan Vladimir or John Vladimir was the ruler of Duklja, the most powerful Serbian principality of the time, from around 1000 to 1016. He ruled during the protracted war between the Byzantine Empire and the First Bulgarian Empire. Wikipedia

K'inich Janaab' Pakal.label: K'inich Janaab' Pakal
K'inich Janaab' Pakal.description: K'inich Janaab' Pakal was ruler of the Maya polity of Palenque in the Late Classic period of pre-Columbian Mesoamerican chronology. Wikipedia

Kanishka II.label: Kanishka II
Kanishka II.description: Kanishka II was one of the emperors of the Kushan Empire from around 225–245 CE. He succeeded Vasudeva I who is considered to be the last great Kushan emperor. It is likely he lost part of his empire to the Kushano-Sassanians. Wikipedia

King Nicias.label: King Nicias
King Nicias.description: Nicias was an Indo-Greek king who ruled in the Paropamisade. Most of his relatively few coins have been found in northern Pakistan, indicating that he ruled a smaller principate around the lower Kabul valley. Wikipedia

Kormisosh of Bulgaria.label: Kormisosh of Bulgaria
Kormisosh of Bulgaria.description:
Kormisosh was a ruler of Bulgaria during the 8th century.
The Namelist of Bulgarian Rulers states that he belonged to the Ukil clan and ruled for 17 years. Wikipedia

Kumaragupta I.label: Kumaragupta I
Kumaragupta I.description: Kumaragupta I was a ruler of the Gupta Empire in 415–455 CE. Like his father and predecessor, Chandragupta II, Kumaragupta was an able ruler. Wikipedia

Enno II, Count of East Frisia.label: Enno II, Count of East Frisia
Enno II, Count of East Frisia.description: Enno II of East Frisia was the son of Edzard I of East Frisia. In 1528 he became count of East Frisia. For most of his life he ruled together with Johan I of East Frisia, who remained Catholic, while Enno was Lutheran. Wikipedia

Leopold II, Prince of Lippe.label: Leopold II, Prince of Lippe
Leopold II, Prince of Lippe.description: Leopold II of Lippe was the sovereign of the Principality of Lippe. He succeeded to the throne in 1802, and in 1820 he assumed control of the government from his mother who had been acting as regent due to his youth at accession. Wikipedia

Meritaten.label: Meritaten
Meritaten.description: Meritaten also spelled Merytaten or Meryetaten was an ancient Egyptian queen of the eighteenth dynasty, who held the position of Great Royal Wife to Pharaoh Smenkhkare, who may have been a brother or son of Akhenaten. Wikipedia

Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado.label: Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado
Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado.description: Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado was the 103rd emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession. His reign spanned the years from 1464 through 1500. Wikipedia

Mircea I of Wallachia.label: Mircea I of Wallachia
Mircea I of Wallachia.description: Mircea the Elder was ruler of Wallachia from 1386 until his death. The byname "elder" was given to him after his death in order to distinguish him from his grandson Mircea II. Wikipedia

Mindaugas.label: Mindaugas
Mindaugas.description: Mindaugas was the first known Grand Duke of Lithuania and the only King of Lithuania. Little is known of his origins, early life, or rise to power; he is mentioned in a 1219 treaty as an elder duke, and in 1236 as the leader of all the Lithuanians. Wikipedia

Lobengula.label: Lobengula
Lobengula.description: Lobengula Khumalo was the second and last king of the Ndebele people, usually called Matabele in English. Wikipedia
Parents: Princess of the Swazi House of Sobhuza I

Mohammed Adil Shah.label: Mohammed Adil Shah
Mohammed Adil Shah.description: Muhammad Adil Shah was the ruler of Bijapur, ascending the throne in 1627 at the comparatively young age of sixteen years. This was accomplished with the help of two Bijapuri nobles – Daulat Khan and Mirza Muhammad Amin Lari. Wikipedia

Mohammed ash-Sheikh.label: Mohammed ash-Sheikh
Mohammed ash-Sheikh.description: Mawlay Mohammed ash-Sheikh ash Sharif al-Hassani al-Drawi at-Tagmaderti was the first sultan of the Saadi dynasty ruling over Morocco. "Al-Drawi at-Tagmadert" means the man from the Draa river valley, from Tagmadert. Wikipedia
Children: Abu Marwan Abd al-Malik I Saadi
People also search for: Abu Marwan Abd al-Malik I Saadi
Al-Hajjam al-Hasan ibn Muhammad ibn al-Qassim

Mussius Aemilianus.label: Mussius Aemilianus
Mussius Aemilianus.description:
Lucius Mussius Aemilianus was a Roman usurper.
Mussius Aemilianus probably was of Italian stock. He was an officer in the Roman army under Philip the Arab and Valerian. Under the latter he became praefect of Egypt. Wikipedia

Muwenda Mutebi II of Buganda.label: Muwenda Mutebi II of Buganda
Muwenda Mutebi II of Buganda.description: Ronald Edward Frederick Kimera Muwenda Mutebi II is the reigning Kabaka of the Kingdom of Buganda, a kingdom in modern-day Uganda. He is the thirty-sixth Kabaka of Buganda. Wikipedia

Nabû-mukin-apli.label: Nabû-mukin-apli
Nabû-mukin-apli.description: Nabû-mukin-apli, typically inscribed dAG-DU-A, “Nabû establisher of a legitimate heir,” 978 – 943 BC, founded Babylon’s 8th dynasty, the so-called Dynasty of E, and ruled for 36 years. Wikipedia

Nabonassar.label: Nabonassar
Nabonassar.description: Nabû-nāṣir, inscribed in cuneiform as dAG-PAB or dAG-ŠEŠ-ir, Greek Ναβονάσσαρος from whence comes "Nabonassar", and meaning "Nabû protector", was the king of Babylon 747–732 BC, beginning a new era characterized by the systematic maintenance of ... Wikipedia

Nabu-mukin-zeri.label: Nabu-mukin-zeri
Nabu-mukin-zeri.description: Nabû-mukin-zēri, inscribed mdAG-DU-NUMUN, also known as Mukin-zēri, was the king of Babylon 731–729 BC. The Ptolemaic Canon gives his name as Χινζηρος. Wikipedia

Neithhotep.label: Neithhotep
Neithhotep.description: Neithhotep was the first queen of ancient Egypt, cofounder of the First dynasty, and is the earliest woman in history whose name is known. The name Neithhotep means "[The Goddess] Neith is satisfied". Wikipedia

Nepotianus.label: Nepotianus
Nepotianus.description: Iulius Nepotianus, commonly known in English as Nepotian, was a member of the Constantinian dynasty who reigned as a short-lived usurper of the Roman Empire. Wikipedia

Ordulf, Duke of Saxony.label: Ordulf, Duke of Saxony
Ordulf, Duke of Saxony.description: Ordulf was the duke of Saxony from 1059, when he succeeded his father Bernard II, until his death. He was a member of the Billung family. Wikipedia

Otto II, Duke of Swabia.label: Otto II, Duke of Swabia
Otto II, Duke of Swabia.description: Otto II was Count Palatine of Lotharingia, then Duke of Swabia, and all the while Count in Deutz and Auelgau. He was the son of Ezzo and Matilda, and a member of the Ezzonian dynasty. Wikipedia

Prince Marko.label: Prince Marko
Prince Marko.description: Marko Mrnjavčević was the de jure Serbian king from 1371 to 1395 and the de facto ruler of territory in western Macedonia centered on the town of Prilep. Wikipedia

Prince Georg of Bavaria.label: Prince Georg of Bavaria
Prince Georg of Bavaria.description: Prince Georg of Bavaria was a member of the Bavarian Royal House of Wittelsbach and a Catholic priest. Wikipedia

Regalianus.label: Regalianus
Regalianus.description: P. C Regalianus was a Dacian general who turned against the Roman Empire and became himself emperor for a brief period, being murdered by the hands who raised him to power. Wikipedia

Ricberht of East Anglia.label: Ricberht of East Anglia
Ricberht of East Anglia.description: Ricberht, may have briefly ruled East Anglia, a small independent Anglo-Saxon kingdom which today includes the English counties of Norfolk and Suffolk. Little is known of his life or his reign. Wikipedia

Robert de Brus, 5th Lord of Annandale.label: Robert de Brus, 5th Lord of Annandale
Robert de Brus, 5th Lord of Annandale.description: Robert V de Brus, 5th Lord of Annandale, was a feudal lord, Justice and Constable of Scotland and England, a Regent of Scotland, and a leading competitor for the Scottish throne in 1290/92 in the Great Cause. Wikipedia
Children: daughter of Robert Bruce 5th Lord of Annandale

Ruaidrí Ua Conchobair.label: Rory O'Connor
Ruaidrí Ua Conchobair.description:
Ruaidrí Ua Conchobair was King of Connacht from 1156 to 1186, and from 1166 to 1183 was the last High King of Ireland before the Norman invasion.
Ruaidrí was one of over twenty sons of King Tairrdelbach Ua Conchobair. Wikipedia

Rudolf Christian, Count of East Frisia.label: Rudolf Christian, Count of East Frisia
Rudolf Christian, Count of East Frisia.description: Rudolf Christian of Ostfriesland, Count of East Frisia, was count of East Frisia, and the second son of Enno III of East Frisia and Anna of Holstein-Gottorp. Wikipedia

Sālote Tupou III.label: Sālote Tupou III
Sālote Tupou III.description: Sālote Mafile‘o Pilolevu Tupou III, GCMG, GCVO, GBE, DStJ, but usually named only Sālote, was queen regnant of Tonga from 5 April 1918 to her death in 1965. Wikipedia

Sa'id of Egypt.label: Sa'id of Egypt
Sa'id of Egypt.description: Muhammad Sa'id Pasha was the Wāli of Egypt and Sudan from 1854 until 1863, officially owing fealty to the Ottoman Sultan but in practice exercising virtual independence. He was the fourth son of Muhammad Ali Pasha. Wikipedia

Sabinianus.label: Sabinianus
Sabinianus.description: Sabinianus was the leader of a revolt against Gordian III in Africa. He proclaimed himself Emperor, but after being defeated by the governor of Mauretania, his supporters in Carthage surrendered him to the imperial authorities. Wikipedia

Sartaq Khan.label: Sartaq Khan
Sartaq Khan.description:
Sartaq Khan was the son of Batu Khan and Regent Dowager Khatun Boraqcin of Alchi Tatar. Sartaq succeeded Batu as khan of the Ulus of Jochi.
In 1252, Alexander Nevsky met with Sartaq at Sarai. Wikipedia

Safdarjung.label: Safdarjung
Safdarjung.description: Safdar Jung was the Subadar Nawab of Oudh from 19 March 1739 to 5 October 1754. Wikipedia

Shammuramat.label: Shammuramat
Shammuramat.description: Shammuramat or Sammu-ramat was a Queen of Assyria between 811 and 808 BCE. Wikipedia

Shu-Ilishu.label: Shu-Ilishu
Shu-Ilishu.description: Šu-ilišu, ca. 1920 BC – 1911 BC, or 1984- 1975 BC was the 2nd ruler of the 1st Dynasty of Isin and reigned for 10 years according to his extant year-names and a single copy of the Sumerian King List, ... Wikipedia

Stephen III of Moldavia.label: Stephen III of Moldavia
Stephen III of Moldavia.description: Stephen III of Moldavia was Prince of Moldavia between 1457 and 1504 and the most prominent representative of the House of Mușat. Wikipedia

Skandagupta.label: Skandagupta
Skandagupta.description: Skandagupta was a Gupta Emperor of northern India. He is generally considered the last of the great Gupta Emperors. Wikipedia

Stephen Uroš V of Serbia.label: Stephen Uroš V of Serbia
Stephen Uroš V of Serbia.description: Saint Stephen Uroš V, also known as Stefan Uroš the Weak, was king of the Serbian Empire as co-regent of his father Stefan Uroš IV Dušan Silni and then Emperor. Wikipedia
Parents: Stephen Uroš IV Dušan of Serbia

Suen-magir.label: Suen-magir
Suen-magir.description: Sîn-māgir, inscribed dEN.ZU-ma-gir, “Sîn upholds,” ca. 1763 – 1753 BC or ca. 1827 – 1817 BC was the 14th king of Isin and he reigned for 11 years. Wikipedia

Suleiman I of Persia.label: Suleiman I of Persia
Suleiman I of Persia.description: Suleiman I was a Safavid shah of Persia who reigned between 1666 and 1694. He was the elder son of the previous shah Abbas II and a Circassian slave, Nakihat Khanum. Wikipedia

Svante Nilsson (regent of Sweden).label: Svante Nilsson
Svante Nilsson (regent of Sweden).description: Svante Nilsson was a Swedish statesman and regent of Sweden 1504 – 2 January 1512. Wikipedia

Taejo of Joseon.label: Taejo of Joseon
Taejo of Joseon.description: Taejo of Joseon, born Yi Seong-gye, whose changed name is Yi Dan, was the founder and the first king of the Joseon Dynasty of Korea, and the main figure in overthrowing the Goryeo Dynasty. Wikipedia

Tahmasp I.label: Tahmasp I
Tahmasp I.description: Tahmasp I was an influential Shah of Iran, who enjoyed the longest reign of any member of the Safavid dynasty. He was the son and successor of Ismail I. Wikipedia
Siblings: Prince ‘Abu'l Fat'h Sultan Moez od-din Bahram Mirza
Children: Princess Shahzadi Alamiyan Fatemeh Sultan Beygom
Princess Shahzadi Alamiyan Mariam Sultan Beygom
Princess Shahzadeh Alamiyan Gowhar Sultan Beygom
Princess Shahzadi Alamiyan Khadija Sultan Begum

Tervel of Bulgaria.label: Tervel of Bulgaria
Tervel of Bulgaria.description: Khan Tervel also called Tarvel, or Terval, or Terbelis in some Byzantine sources, was the Emperor of the Bulgarians at the beginning of the 8th century. In 705 Emperor Justinian II named him Caesar, the first foreigner to receive this title. Wikipedia

Tahmasp II.label: Tahmasp II
Tahmasp II.description: Tahmasp II or Tahmasebi II was one of the last Safavid rulers of Persia. Tahmasp was the son of Sultan Husayn, the Shah of Iran at that time. When Husayn was forced to abdicate by the Afghans in 1722, Prince Tahmasp wished to claim the throne. Wikipedia

Theophilos (king).label: Theophilos
Theophilos (king).description: Theophilos was a minor Indo-Greek king who ruled for a short time in the Paropamisadae. He was possibly a relative of Zoilos I and is only known from coins. Wikipedia

Thurisind.label: Thurisind
Thurisind.description: Thurisind was king of the Gepids, an East Germanic Gothic people, from c. 548 to 560. He was the penultimate Gepid king, and succeeded King Elemund by staging a coup d'état and forcing the king's son into exile. Wikipedia

Tiglath-Pileser I.label: Tiglath-Pileser I
Tiglath-Pileser I.description: Tiglath-Pileser I was a king of Assyria during the Middle Assyrian period. According to Georges Roux, Tiglath-Pileser was "one of the two or three great Assyrian monarchs since the days of Shamshi-Adad I". Wikipedia

Ur-Ninurta.label: Ur-Ninurta
Ur-Ninurta.description: Ur-Ninurta, ca. 1859 – 1832 BC or ca. 1923 – 1896 BC, was the 6th king of the 1st Dynasty of Isin. A usurper, Ur-Ninurta seized the throne on the fall of Lipit-Ištar and held it until his violent death some 28 years later. Wikipedia

Vima Takto.label: Vima Takto
Vima Takto.description: Vima Takto or Vima Taktu was a Kushan emperor reigned c. 80–90 CE. Wikipedia

Mutara II Rwogera.label: Mutara II Rwogera
Mutara II Rwogera.description: Mutara II Rwogera was the King of Rwanda from 1830 to 1853. Wikipedia

Toktu of Bulgaria.label: Toktu of Bulgaria
Toktu of Bulgaria.description:
Toktu was the ruler of Bulgaria between 766–767.
The Byzantine chronicler Patriarch Nikephoros records that Toktu was "a Bulgarian, and a brother of Bayan". Wikipedia

Edzard II, Count of East Frisia.label: Edzard II, Count of East Frisia
Edzard II, Count of East Frisia.description:
Edzard II, Count of East Frisia was count of East Frisia, and the son of Enno II of East Frisia and Anna of Oldenburg.
During his reign, he came into conflict with the city of Emden. Wikipedia
